(:kind :chapter :book "Reference Manual" :chapter-number 7 :title "Chapter 7 — Streams" :source-path "git://origin/main/scheme-books/reference/07-streams.md" :size 2835 :sha256 "03eabbace60e35e9" :content "---\nslug: sakura-scheme-book-reference-07\ntitle: Streams\nbook: reference\nchapter: 7\nof: 16\npart: I\napp: scheme-repl\npalette: book-standard\ncanonical: true\nowner: docs-team (Lane Q9)\nstatus: draft\nlast-reviewed: 2026-07-10\nprev: 06-metacircular\nnext: 08-continuations\n---\n\n# Chapter 7 — Streams\n\nStreams are lists that are only partially computed. This chapter is about the shape.\n\n> **Sakura says**\n>\n> A stream is a list that remembers how to compute more of itself when asked. That laziness is what lets it be infinite without exhausting memory.\n\n## The stream\n\n```scheme\n(define (make-stream head tail-thunk) (cons head tail-thunk))\n(define (stream-head s) (car s))\n(define (stream-tail s) ((cdr s)))\n\n(define ones (make-stream 1 (lambda () ones)))\n(display (stream-head ones)) (newline)\n(display (stream-head (stream-tail ones))) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n1\n1\n```\n\nInfinite ones. Only compute what you look at.\n\n## The naturals\n\n```scheme\n(define (integers-from n)\n  (make-stream n (lambda () (integers-from (+ n 1)))))\n\n(define naturals (integers-from 1))\n\n(display (stream-head naturals)) (newline)\n(display (stream-head (stream-tail naturals))) (newline)\n(display (stream-head (stream-tail (stream-tail naturals)))) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n1\n2\n3\n```\n\n## Take\n\n```scheme\n(define (stream-take n s)\n  (cond ((= n 0) '())\n        (else (cons (stream-head s)\n                    (stream-take (- n 1) (stream-tail s))))))\n\n(display (stream-take 5 naturals)) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n(1 2 3 4 5)\n```\n\nTake the first 5. The rest of the stream is untouched.\n\n## Map on streams\n\n```scheme\n(define (stream-map f s)\n  (make-stream (f (stream-head s))\n               (lambda () (stream-map f (stream-tail s)))))\n\n(display (stream-take 5 (stream-map (lambda (x) (* x x)) naturals))) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n(1 4 9 16 25)\n```\n\nSquares of naturals — first five.\n\n## Filter on streams\n\n```scheme\n(define (stream-filter pred s)\n  (cond ((pred (stream-head s))\n         (make-stream (stream-head s)\n                       (lambda () (stream-filter pred (stream-tail s)))))\n        (else (stream-filter pred (stream-tail s)))))\n\n(display (stream-take 5 (stream-filter odd? naturals))) (newline)\n```\n\nOutput:\n\n```\n(1 3 5 7 9)\n```\n\n## What you know now\n\n- Streams are lazy lists.\n- Cons with a thunk instead of a computed tail.\n- Take, map, filter all work as on lists.\n- Streams enable infinite structures without exhausting memory.\n\n## Try before you turn the page\n\n```scheme\n(display '(stream-is-a-list-that-remembers-how-to-grow)) (newline)\n```\n\nIf you can define naturals as a stream, you're ready for continuations.\n\n---\n\nCross-references:\n\n- [[book-of-reference#chapter-3]] — tail-recursion.\n- [[book-of-reference#chapter-6]] — metacircular.\n- [[book-of-motion#chapter-9]] — timing-and-counters is a stream in disguise.\n")
